[05:09] <allison> Parrot has been through several phases in calling conventions
[05:09] <cotto> Getting something working is my current priority now, but getting something that *can* be efficient is next on the list.
[05:10] <allison> from "just stuff it in a register"
[05:10] <allison> to stuff it in a limited range of registers
[05:10] <allison> to stuff it in registers with overflow in a PMC
[05:11] <allison> to what was meant to be an elegant solution where no copies were made and callee just pulled values from caller
[05:11] <allison> (but actually turned out to be a horrible mess because there were several different ways that callers could pass arguments to callees)
[05:12] <cotto> This is highly relevant.
[05:12] <cotto> thanks
[05:12] <allison> (and we ended up passing partially consumed varargs around through nasty waves of code)
[05:13] <allison> and in reaction to that mess, we moved on to the current strategy, with a single standard "intermediate storage" location for arguments
[05:14] <allison> so that caller only has to know how to store things in the standard form
[05:14] *** klavs left
[05:14] <allison> and callee only has to know how to retrieve things from the standard form
[05:14] <allison> the problem being, that the standard form is GC-able
[05:14] <allison> and so, puts more pressure on the already stressed GC
[05:16] <cotto> and here we are
[05:16] <allison> it could be possible to alleviate that by making the intermediate storage a special "short-lived" GC-able like we talked about for contexts
[05:17] <allison> or, by actually making it the context
[05:17] <allison> either, caller creates the context and directly stores the arguments in registers
[05:17] <allison> or, context has some additional "argument" storage
[05:18] <allison> having the caller take responsibility for setting up the context and arguments and things is problematic though, because it doesn't allow for variation
